Go Does Not Need a Java Style GC

Why does Go not need a fancy expensive garbage collector like Java and C#?

Modern languages such as Go, Julia and Rust don’t need complex garbage collectors like the ones use by Java C#. But why?

To explain why, we need to get into how garbage collectors work and how different languages allocate memory in different ways. However, we will start by looking at why Java in particular needs such a complex garbage collector.

I will cover a lot of different garbage collector topics here:

  • Why Java is so dependent on a fast GC. I will cover some of the design choices in the Java language itself that create a lot of pressure on the GC.
  • Memory fragmentation and how that impacts GC design. Why this matters a lot for Java but much less for Go.
  • Value types and how they change the GC game.
  • Generational Garbage collectors and why Go doesn’t need one.
  • Escape analysis — A trick used by Go to reduce pressure on GC.
  • Compacting Garbage Collectors — Important in the Java world but somehow Go avoids the need for it. Why?
  • Concurrent Garbage Collection — How Go solves a lot of GC challenges by running a concurrent Garbage collector using multiple threads. Why this is much harder to do with Java.
  • Common criticisms of the Go GC and why a lot of the assumptions behind that critique is often flawed or plain wrong.

Why Java Needs a Fast GC More Than Everybody Else

Java is a language that basically outsourced memory management entirely to its garbage collector. This turned out to be a big mistake. However, to be able to explain why, I need to cover more of the details.

Let us start at the beginning. It is 1991 and the work on Java has begun. Garbage collectors are all the rage. Research looks very promising and the designers of Java are placing their bets on advanced garbage collectors being able to solve essentially all challenges in managing memory.

For this reason, all objects in Java are designed to be allocated on the heap, with the exception of primitive types such as integers and floating point values. When talking about memory allocation, we generally distinguish between what is called the heap and the stack. The stack is very fast to use, but has limited space and can only be used for objects that do not need to exist beyond the lifetime of a function call. It is only for local variables. The heap can be used for all objects. Java basically ignored the stack and chose to allocate everything on the heap, except primitives like integers and floats. Whenever you write new Something() in Java, you are consuming memory on the heap.

However, this type of memory management is actually quite expensive in terms of memory usage. You would think that creating an object with only a 32-bit integer would only require 4 bytes of memory.

class Knight {
   int health;
}

However ,in order for the garbage collector to work, Java stores a header with information such as:

  • Type — To identify the class or type of the object.
  • Lock — Used in synchronize statements.
  • Mark — Used during mark and sweep face of the garbage collector.

This data typically amount to 16 bytes. Hence there is a ratio of 4:1 in header data to actual data. The C++ source code for a Java object defined as: OpenJDK Base Class.

class oopDesc {
    volatile markOop  _mark;   // for mark and sweep
    Klass*           _klass;   // the type
}

Memory Fragmentation

The next problem is memory fragmentation. When Java allocates an array of objects, what it really does is create an array of references pointing to objects at some other location in memory. These objects could end up scattered around heap memory. That is bad for performance because modern microprocessors don't read individual bytes of data. Because initiating a memory transfer is slow, the microprocessor always reads a large contiguous block of memory each time it tries to access one particular memory location.

This block of memory is called a cache line. The CPU has its own highspeed memory called cache. This is of a much smaller size than main memory. It is used to store the most recently accessed objects, because those are likely to get accessed again. If main memory is fragmented, that means cache lines will be fragmented and the CPU cache will get filled up with lots of useless data.

How Java overcomes memory fragmentation

To deal with these major disadvantages, Java maintainers have invested a ton of money into advanced garbage collectors. These do something called compaction. Compaction involves moving objects around memory and collect them into contiguous blocks a memory. This is not cheap. Not only does moving the blocks from one memory location to another cost CPU cycles, but updating every reference to these objects to point to the new locations also costs CPU cycles.

Doing these updates requires freezing all threads. You cannot update references while they are being used. This typically causes Java programs to have complete freezes of several hundred milliseconds where objects get moved around, references updated and unused memory reclaimed.

Adding Complexity

To reduce these long pauses, Java uses what is called generational garbage collectors. These are based on the following premise:

that most values allocated in a program are quickly unused, so there is an advantage for the GC to spend more time looking at recently allocated objects.

That is why Java partition their allocated objects into two groups:

  • Old objects — Objects that have survived multiple mark and sweep operations by the GC. A generation counter is updated on each mark and sweep to keep track of how old the objects are.
  • Young objects — These have a low generation counter. Meaning they have only recently been allocated.

Java more actively investigates recently allocated objects and checks whether they should be reclaimed or moved. As objects age, they get moved out of the young generation area.

All of this naturally creates more complexity. It requires more development. It requires paying for more talented developers, costing more money.

How Modern Languages Avoided The Same Pitfalls as Java

Modern languages don’t need complex garbage collectors like Java and C#. This is because they have not been designed to rely on them to the same extent.

// Go: Make an an array of 15 000 Point objects intype Point struct {
    X, Y int
}var points [15000]Point

In the Go code example above, we allocate 15 000 Point objects. This is just one single allocation, producing a single pointer. In Java, this requires 15 000 separate allocations, each producing a separate reference that must be managed. Every Point object gets the 16-byte header overhead I wrote about earlier. Neither in Go, Julia or Rust do you get this overhead. The objects are generally header-less.

In Java, the GC gets 15 000 separate objects it must track and manage. Go only has 1 object to track.

Value Types

The reason why this is possible in other languages is because they support value types. The code below defines a rectangle with a Min and Max point defining its extent.

type Rect struct {
   Min, Max Point
}

This becomes one contiguous block of memory. In Java, this would turn into a Rect object with references to two separate objects, the Min and the Max point objects. Thus in Java, an instance of Rect would require 3 allocations, but only 1 allocation in Go, Rust, C/C++ and Julia.

The lack of value types created significant problems when porting Git to Java. Without value types, it was hard to get good performance. As Shawn O. Pearce remarks on the JGit developer mailing list:

JGit struggles with not having an efficient way to represent a SHA-1. C can just say unsigned char[20] and have it inline into the container's memory allocation. A byte[20] in Java will cost an additional 16 bytes of memory, and be slower to access because the bytes themselves are in a different area of memory from the container object. We try to work around it by converting from a byte[20] to 5 ints, but that costs us machine instructions.

What are we talking about there? In Go, I can do the same thing as C/C++ and define a structure like this:

type Sha1 struct {
   data [20]byte
}

Those bytes will then be part of one block of memory. Java will create a pointer to somewhere else in memory.

Java developers realize they screwed up and that you really need value types for good performance. You can call that statement hyperbole, but then you need to explain Project Valhalla. This is an effort spearheaded by Oracle to give Java value types and the reasons they articulate for doing so point exactly to what I am talking about here.

Value Types Are Not Enough

So will Project Valhalla solve Java’s problems? Not really. It will simply put Java on equal footing with C#. C# came out years after Java and had since realized that garbage collectors were not quite the magic everybody thought they would be. Thus they added value types.

However, this does not put C# and Java on equal footing with languages like Go and C/C++ in terms of memory management flexibility. Java does not support real pointers. In Go, I can write something like this:

// Go pointer usagevar ptr *Point = &rect.Min // Store pointer to Min in ptr
*ptr = Point(2, 4)         // replace rect.Min

You can take the address of objects or fields of objects in Go, just like in C/C++ and store it in a pointer. You can then pass this pointer around and use it to modify the fields it points to. This means you can create large value objects in Go and pass it as a pointer to function to optimize performance. With C# the situation is a bit better as it has limited support for pointers. The previous Go example could be written in C# as:

// C# pointer usageunsafe void foo() {
   Rect* ptr = &rect.Min;
   *ptr = new Point(2, 4);
}

However C# pointer support comes with a number of caveats which does not apply to Go:

  1. Code using points must be marked as unsafe. This creates code with less safety and more likely to crash.
  2. Pure value types allocated on the stack (all struct fields must be value types).
  3. Within a fixed scope, where garbage collection has been turned off, using the fixed keyword.

Thus the normal and safe way to use value types in C# is to copy them, as this does not require defining unsafe or fixed code regions. But for larger value types this can create performance problems. Go does not have these issues. You can make pointers to objects managed by the garbage collector in Go. You don’t need to isolate code using pointers in Go, like in C#.

Custom Secondary Allocators

With proper pointers, you can do a lot of things which is not possible when you only have value types. One example is to create secondary allocators. Here is an example of an Arena allocator created using Go generics.

type Arena[T any] struct {
    blocks Stack[*T]
}func (arena *Arena[T]) Alloc() *T {
    if arena.blocks.IsEmpty() {
        var blocks [32]T     // allocate 32 elements at a time
        for i, _ := range blocks {
            arena.blocks.Push(&blocks[i])
        }
    }
    b, _ := arena.blocks.Top()
    arena.blocks.Pop()    return b
}

Why are these useful? If you look at microbenchmarks for algorithms making binary trees, you will typically see that Java has a big advantage over Go. That is because binary tree algorithms are usually used to test speed of garbage collector in allocating objects. Java is very fast at this because it uses what we call a bump pointer. It just increments a pointer while Go will search for a suitable place in memory to allocate the object. However, with an Arena allocator, you can quickly build a binary tree in Go as well.

import "golang.org/x/exp/constraints"type Tree[K constraints.Ordered, V any] struct {
    Root      *TreeNode[K, V]
    allocator Arena[TreeNode[K, V]]
}func (tree *Tree[K, V]) NewNode(key K, value V) *TreeNode[K, V] {
    n := tree.allocator.Alloc()
    n.Key = key
    n.Value = value
    n.left = nil
    n.right = nil    return n
}func (tree *Tree[K, V]) Insert(key K, value V) {
    n := tree.NewNode(key, value)    if tree.Root == nil {
        tree.Root = n
    } else {
        tree.Root.Insert(n)
    }
}

This is why having real pointers have a benefit. You cannot create a pointer to an element in a contiguous block of memory without it. In the Alloc method we create a contiguous block of 32 elements. We then store a pointer to to each element in this block on a stack holding a list of block available for allocation.

var blocks [32]T
for i, _ := range blocks {
    arena.blocks.Push(&blocks[i])
}

This is only possible because I can pick an arbitrary elements blocks[i] and get the pointer to that element &blocks[i]. Java does not give you this possibility.

Problem with Java Bump Allocators

A bump allocator used by the Java GC is similar in that just like an Arena allocator you just increment a pointer to get the next value. Except you don’t have to build it yourself. This may seem more clever. But it causes several problems avoided in Go:

  1. Sooner or later you need to do compaction, which involves moving data around and fixing pointers. An Arena allocator does not have to do that.
  2. In a multithreaded program, a bump allocator requires locks (unless you use thread local storage). That kills their performance advantage, either because locks degrade performance or thread local storage will cause fragmentation, which needs to be compacted later.

Ian Lance Taylor, one of the creators of Go clarifies the problem with bump allocators:

In general it’s likely to be more efficient to allocate memory using a set of per-thread caches, and at that point you’ve lost the advantages of a bump allocator. So I would assert that, in general, with many caveats, there is no real advantage to using a compacting memory allocator for a multi-threaded program today.

Generational GC and Escape Analysis

The Java garbage collector has a lot more work to do because it allocates a lot more objects. Why? We just covered that. Without value objects and real pointers, it will always end up with a huge number of objects when allocating large arrays or complex data structures. Thus it needs a Generational GC.

The need to allocate fewer objects plays to Go’s advantage. But there is another trick Go utilizes. Both Go and Java do what is called escape analysis when compiling a function.

Escape analysis involves looking at pointers created inside a function and determining whether that pointer ever escapes the function scope.

func escapingPtr() []int {
   values := []int{4, 5, 10}
   return values
}

fun nonEscapingPtr() int {
    values = []int{4, 5, 10}
    var total int = addUp(values)
    return total
}

In the first example, values points to a slice, which is essentially the same as a pointer to an array. It escapes because it is returned. That means values has to be allocated on the heap.

However, in the second example, no pointer to values ever leaves the nonEscapingPtr function. Thus values can be allocated on the stack, which is very quick and cheap. Escape analysis itself is only analyzing whether a pointer escapes or not.

Limitations of Java Escape Analysis

Java does escape analysis as well but has more limitations on its usage. From Java SE 16 Oracle documentation covering the HotSpot VM:

It does not replace a heap allocation with a stack allocation for objects that do not globally escape.

However Java uses an alternative trick called scalar-replacement, which avoids the need to place objects on the stack. Essentially it explodes and object and puts its primitive members on the stack. Remember Java can already put primitive values such as int and float on the stack. However in practice scalar replacement does not work even in very trivial cases, as discovered by Piotr Kołaczkowski in 2021.

Instead the primary advantage is in avoiding locks. If you know a pointer isn’t used outside a function you can also determine that it does not need a lock.

Advantage of Go Escape Analysis

Go, however, uses escape analysis to determine which objects can be allocated on the stack. That significantly cuts down on the number of short-lived objects that would have benefited from a Generational GC. Remember that the whole point of a Generational GC is to exploit the fact that recently allocated objects live a short time. However, most objects in Go are likely going to live long, because the short-lived ones are likely caught by the escape analysis.

Unlike Java this also works for complex object. Java can typically only successfully do escape analysis for simple objects like a byte array. Even built in ByteBuffer cannot be allocated on stack using scalar replacement.

Modern Languages Don’t Need Compacting GCs

You can read a lot of experts on garbage collectors claiming that Go is more likely to run out of memory than Java due to memory fragmentation. The argument goes something like this: because Go does not have a compacting garbage collector, memory will become fragmented over time. When memory is fragmented you will reach a point where fitting a new object into memory will become hard.

However, this problem is drastically reduced for two reasons:

  1. Go does not allocate as many tiny objects as Java. It can allocate large arrays of objects as a single block of memory.
  2. Modern memory allocators such as Google’s TCMalloc or Intel’s Scalable Malloc do not fragment memory.

Back when Java was designed, memory fragmentation was a big problem with memory allocators. People did not think it could be solved. But even back in 1998, shortly after Java came out, researchers started solving this problem. Here is a paper from Mark S. Johnstone and Paul R. Wilson:

This substantially strengthens our previous results showing that the memory fragmentation problem has generally been misunderstood, and that good allocator policies can provide good memory usage for most programs.

Thus a lot of assumptions that went into designing the memory allocation strategies for Java are simply no longer true.

Generational GC vs Concurrent GC Pauses

The Java strategy of using a Generational GC is meant to keep the garbage collection periods shorter. Remember that Java has to stop everything to move data around and fix pointers. This kills performance and responsiveness if it keeps on for too long. With a Generational GC, there is less data to inspect each time cutting this time down.

However Go solves the same problem with a number of alternative strategies:

  1. Because no memory has to be moved and no pointers fixed, there is less work to do during GC runs. Go GC only does a mark and sweep: it looks looks through the object graph for objects that should be released.
  2. It runs concurrently. Thus, a separate GC thread can look for objects to free without stopping the other threads.

Why can Go run its GC concurrently and not Java? Because Go does not fix any pointers or move any objects in memory. Hence there is no risk of trying to access a pointer to an object that has just been moved, but where that pointer has not yet been updated. Objects for which there are no longer any references to will not suddenly get a reference due to some concurrent thread running. Hence there is no danger in removing dead objects in parallel.

How does this play out? Say you have 4 threads doing work in a Go program. One of the threads does occasional GC work for a total of 4 seconds for some time arbitrary time period T seconds.

Now imagine a Java program with a GC doing GC work for only 2 seconds. Which program squeezes out most performance? Who gets most done in T seconds? Sounds like the Java program, right? Wrong!

The 4 working threads in the Java program get all their work stopped for 2 seconds. That means 2×4 = 8 seconds of work gets lost in the T interval. Thus, while Go has longer time stopped, each stop impacts less work, because all the threads are not stopped. Thus a slow concurrent GC will likely outperform a faster GC that relies on stopping all the threads to do its work.

What if Garbage is Created Faster Than Go Can Clean It Up?

One popular argument against current garbage collectors is that you can get into a situation where the active working threads produce garbage quicker than the garbage collector thread can collect the garbage. In the Java world, this is called “concurrent mode failure”.

The claim is that in this case the runtime has no choice but to stop your program entirely and wait for the GC cycle to complete. Thus when Go claims GC pauses are very low, this claim can only be true for the case where the GC has sufficient CPU time and headroom to outrun the main program.

But Go has a clever trick to get around this described by Go GC guru Rick Hudson. Go uses what is called a Pacer.

If need be, the Pacer slows down allocation while speeding up marking. At a high level the Pacer stops the Goroutine, which is doing a lot of the allocation, and puts it to work doing marking. The amount of work is proportional to the Goroutine’s allocation. This speeds up the garbage collector while slowing down the mutator.

Goroutines are kind of like green threads multiplexed over a thread pool. Basically Go takes over the threads that are running workloads that produce a lot of garbage and puts them to work in aiding the GC in cleaning up that garbage. It will just keep taking over threads until the GC runs faster than the routines producing garbage.

In Short

While advanced garbage collectors solve real problems in Java, modern languages such as Go and Julia have simply avoided creating those problems in the first place and thus removed the need to have a Rolls Royce garbage collector. When you have value types, escape analysis, pointers, multi-core processors, and modern allocators, then a lot of the assumptions behind the Java design are out the window. They no longer apply.

Assumed GC Tradeoffs No Longer Apply

Mike Hearn has a very popular story here on Medium criticizing the claims about the Go GC: Modern garbage collection..

Hearn’s key message is that there are always tradeoffs in GC design. The point he makes is that because Go has aimed for low latency collection they will suffer on lots of other metrics. It is an interesting read because it covers a lot of details about tradeoffs in GC design.

First, what do I mean by low latency? The Go GC only pauses around 0.5 milliseconds on average compared to various Java collectors that can spend hundreds of milliseconds.

The problem I see with Mike Hearn’s arguments is that they are based on the flawed premise that memory access patterns are the same across all languages. As I have covered in this article, that is simply not true. Go will produce a lot fewer objects to manage by the GC and it will clean a lot of them up early using escape analysis.

Old Techniques Are Inherently Bad?

Hearn makes arguments that suggest that a simple collect is somehow inherently bad:

Stop-the-world (STW) mark/sweep is the GC algorithm most commonly taught in undergrad computer science classes. When doing job interviews I sometimes ask candidates to talk a bit about GC and almost always, they either see GC as a black box and know nothing about it at all, or think it still uses this by now very old technique.

Yes, it may be old, but this technique allows you to run the GC concurrently, which “modern” techniques don’t allow. In our modern hardware world with multiple cores, that matters more.

Go is Not C#

Another claim:

As Go is a relatively ordinary imperative language with value types, its memory access patterns are probably comparable to C# where the generational hypothesis certainly holds and thus .NET uses a generational collector.

This is not quite the case. A C# developer would minimize usage of larger value objects, as pointer related code cannot be used safely. We must assume C# developers will prefer copying value types rather than using pointers, as this can be done safely within the CLR. This will naturally carry a higher overhead.

C# to my knowledge also does not utilize escape analysis to reduce production of short lived objects on the heap. Secondly, C# is just not as good at running lots of tasks concurrently. Go can utilize their coroutines to speed up collection concurrently, as mentioned with the Pacer.

Compaction

Compaction: as there’s no compaction, your program can eventually fragment its heap. I’ll talk about heap fragmentation more below. You also don’t benefit from having things laid out neatly in the cache.

Here Mike Hearn is simply not up to date on the current state of allocators. Modern allocators such as TCMalloc have basically eliminated this problem.

Program throughput: as the GC has to do a lot of work for every cycle, that steals CPU time from the program itself, slowing it down.

This does not apply when you have a concurrent GC. All other threads can keep running while the GC does its work — unlike Java, which has to stop the world.

Heap Overhead

Hearn brings up the “concurrent mode failure” problem, assuming the Go GC will risk not keeping pace with garbage producers.

Heap overhead: because collecting the heap via mark/sweep is very slow, you need lots of spare space to ensure you don’t suffer a “concurrent mode failure”. Go defaults to a heap overhead of 100% … it doubles the amount of memory your program needs.

I am suspicious of this claim as so many real world examples I see seems to suggest Go programs use less memory. Not to mention this ignores the existence of the Pacer which will grab Goroutines producing lots of garbage and make them clean up instead.

Why Low Latency Matters Even for Java

We live in a world of docker containers and micro-services. That means lots of smaller programs communicate and do work for each other. Imagine work going through several services. Every time just one of these services in one chain has a significant pause, that has a rippling effect. It causes all other processes to halt work. The next service in a pipeline cannot do work if it is waiting for a service busy doing garbage collection.

Thus the latency/throughput tradeoff is no longer a tradeoff in GC design. With multiple services working together, high latency will cause throughput to drop. The Java preference for high throughput and high latency GC applies to a monolith world. It no longer applies in the micro-service world.

This is one fundamental problem with Mike Hearn’s argument that there is no magic bullet and only tradeoffs. It tries to give the impression that the Java tradeoffs are equally valid. But tradeoffs have to be tailored to the world we live in.

In short, I think it is fair to say that Go has made a number of smart moves and strategic choices. Waving it off as if it is just tradeoffs that anybody could have made doesn’t cut it.
